    group: "Unemployment & Labour",
    term: "Involuntary unemployment",
    brief: "Unemployment where workers are willing to accept jobs at the prevailing wage but cannot find them because insufficient jobs exist.",
    more: "Involuntary unemployment arises when aggregate demand is too low to employ all willing workers, or when wages are sticky downwards and cannot fall to clear the market. It is the central concern of Keynesian economics.",
    detailed: "Keynes argued that wages do not adjust quickly enough to eliminate excess labour supply, leaving workers involuntarily unemployed during recessions. Even if workers accept lower wages, falling incomes reduce aggregate demand further, worsening unemployment: this links to the paradox of thrift and the limits of wage cuts. Involuntary unemployment justifies demand-management policies; fiscal or monetary expansion can raise output and create jobs. In contrast, classical economists argue that flexible wages would prevent involuntary unemployment from persisting. Common mistake: Students confuse involuntary unemployment with all unemployment, but frictional and some structural unemployment may be voluntary, as workers search for better matches.",
