    term: "Labour Force Survey measure",
    brief: "A measure of unemployment based on a quarterly household survey using the ILO definition: people without work who are actively seeking and available to start within two weeks.",
    more: "The Labour Force Survey provides the UK's official unemployment rate and is internationally comparable because it applies a standardised definition across countries. It captures unemployed people regardless of whether they claim benefits, giving a broader picture than the claimant count.",
    detailed: "The ILO definition requires three conditions: being out of work, actively seeking work in the past four weeks, and being available to start within two weeks. This captures discouraged workers who stop claiming benefits but continue searching. The survey also measures economic inactivity, employment rates, and underemployment. Because it is sample-based, it is subject to sampling error and published with a lag, making the claimant count more timely for spotting turning points. Common mistake: Students assume the Labour Force Survey and claimant count measure the same thing; the LFS uses a standardised definition unaffected by benefit rules, so the two figures can diverge significantly.",
