    term: "Liquid assets",
    brief: "Assets that can be converted into cash quickly and at minimal cost without significant loss of value.",
    more: "Cash is perfectly liquid; government bonds and money market instruments are highly liquid; property and machinery are illiquid because selling them takes time and may require accepting a lower price. Banks must hold sufficient liquid assets to meet depositor withdrawals and short-term obligations.",
    detailed: "Liquidity matters because a mismatch between liquid assets and short-term liabilities can cause a liquidity crisis, even for a solvent institution. Banks transform liquid deposits into illiquid loans, making them inherently vulnerable to bank runs if depositors lose confidence. Regulators require banks to meet liquidity coverage ratios, holding enough high-quality liquid assets to survive 30 days of stressed outflows. The 2008 financial crisis revealed that assets thought to be liquid, such as mortgage-backed securities, can become illiquid when markets freeze. Common mistake: Students confuse liquidity with solvency; an institution can be solvent (assets exceed liabilities) but fail if it cannot meet immediate cash demands.",
