    term: "Long-run trend rate of growth",
    brief: "The average annual rate at which an economy's productive potential expands over time, smoothing out cyclical fluctuations.",
    more: "For the UK, the long-run trend rate has historically been around 2 to 2.5% per year, though it has slowed since the 2008 financial crisis. It reflects underlying improvements in productivity, capital accumulation, and labour force growth.",
    detailed: "The trend rate provides a benchmark against which actual growth can be assessed: growth above trend closes a negative output gap or creates a positive one, while growth below trend does the reverse. Factors that can shift the trend rate include demographic change, investment rates, educational attainment, and the pace of technological progress. A falling trend rate is concerning because it implies lower future living standards than previously expected. Policymakers debate whether the post-2008 productivity slowdown represents a permanent reduction in the trend rate or a prolonged cyclical effect. Common mistake: Students sometimes treat the trend rate as fixed; it changes over time as structural conditions in the economy evolve.",
    seeAlso: ["long-run-economic-growth", "productivity", "output-gap", "economic-cycle", "supply-side-policies"],
