    group: "Money & Monetary Policy",
    term: "Monetary policy",
    brief: "The use of interest rates, money supply, and credit conditions by the central bank to influence aggregate demand and inflation.",
    more: "The Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee sets Bank Rate to achieve the 2% CPI inflation target. Lower interest rates stimulate borrowing and spending; higher rates restrain demand and reduce inflationary pressure.",
    detailed: "Monetary policy works through several transmission channels: lower rates reduce mortgage and loan costs, encouraging consumption and investment; they weaken the exchange rate, boosting exports; and they raise asset prices, increasing wealth and confidence. When rates hit their lower bound, central banks use unconventional tools like quantitative easing. Monetary policy affects the economy with time lags of 18 to 24 months, requiring policymakers to act on forecasts rather than current conditions. Its effectiveness depends on the responsiveness of borrowing and spending to interest rate changes. Common mistake: Students sometimes treat monetary policy as solely about interest rates; it also encompasses forward guidance, quantitative easing, and macroprudential tools affecting credit conditions.",
    seeAlso: ["bank-rate", "quantitative-easing", "inflation-targeting", "transmission-mechanism-of-monetary-policy", "aggregate-demand"],
