    curricula: ['aqa-alevel', 'ap-economics'],
    group: "Money & Monetary Policy",
    term: "Monetary policy transmission mechanism",
    brief: "The channels through which changes in Bank Rate and other monetary policy tools affect aggregate demand, output, and inflation.",
    more: "The main channels include the interest rate channel (affecting borrowing and saving decisions), the exchange rate channel (affecting net exports), the asset price channel (affecting wealth and collateral values), and the expectations channel (affecting inflation expectations and wage-setting). The strength and speed of transmission varies across channels and economic conditions.",
    detailed: "When Bank Rate rises, the interest rate channel works through higher mortgage payments reducing disposable income and higher borrowing costs deterring investment. The exchange rate channel operates as higher UK rates attract capital inflows, appreciating sterling and reducing export competitiveness. The asset price channel transmits through falling house and equity prices, reducing household wealth and the collateral available for borrowing. The expectations channel matters because credible monetary policy anchors inflation expectations, affecting wage negotiations and price-setting behaviour. Transmission lags mean policy changes take 18 to 24 months to have full effect, requiring the MPC to act pre-emptively. Common mistake: Students often focus only on the interest rate channel; the exchange rate and expectations channels can be equally important, especially in an open economy like the UK.",
    seeAlso: ["bank-rate", "monetary-policy", "exchange-rate", "aggregate-demand", "inflation-expectations"],
