    more: "Central banks influence the money supply through monetary policy, particularly interest rates and quantitative easing. An expanding money supply, if it outpaces output growth, can fuel inflation.",
    detailed: "The money supply is measured in different ways depending on how liquid the assets included are. Narrow money captures the most liquid forms used directly for transactions, while broad money includes less liquid deposits that can be converted to spending relatively quickly. Commercial banks create money through lending: when a bank makes a loan, it credits the borrower's account, increasing deposits and thus the money supply. The quantity theory of money posits that, in the long run, money supply growth determines inflation if velocity and output are stable. Common mistake: Students assume only the central bank creates money; in practice, most money is created by commercial banks through the lending process.",
