    group: "International Economics",
    term: "Multinational corporation (MNC)",
    brief: "A firm that owns or controls production facilities in more than one country, operating across national borders.",
    more: "MNCs locate different stages of production where costs are lowest or markets are largest, exploiting economies of scale and differences in labour costs, tax regimes, and regulations. They account for a significant share of world trade, much of it intra-firm transfers between subsidiaries.",
    detailed: "MNCs can benefit host countries through foreign direct investment, job creation, technology transfer, and tax revenues. However, they may also suppress wages, extract profits to low-tax jurisdictions, and wield political influence that distorts policy. Transfer pricing, the practice of setting artificial prices for transactions between subsidiaries, allows MNCs to shift profits to minimise tax, reducing revenues in higher-tax countries. Developing countries often compete to attract MNCs through tax incentives and relaxed regulations, raising concerns about a race to the bottom. The bargaining power between MNCs and governments depends on how mobile the investment is and how much the host country needs it. Common mistake: Students assume MNCs are always exploitative; their impact depends heavily on the regulatory environment and bargaining power of the host country.",
