    more: "Narrow money measures assets that can be used immediately for transactions without conversion. In the UK, narrow money is captured by the M0 measure, which includes notes, coins, and commercial banks' reserve balances at the Bank of England.",
    detailed: "Narrow money represents the monetary base over which the central bank has direct control: it can increase or decrease narrow money by buying or selling assets. Because narrow money excludes bank deposits created through lending, it is much smaller than broad money. Changes in narrow money do not translate directly into spending; the relationship depends on how much banks lend and how the public chooses to hold money between cash and deposits. Common mistake: Students conflate narrow money with the total money supply. Narrow money is the base, and the broader money supply is a multiple of it, determined by banking activity.",
