    term: "National debt",
    brief: "The total accumulated borrowing of a government, representing the sum of all past budget deficits minus surpluses.",
    more: "Each year a government runs a budget deficit, it adds to the national debt by issuing bonds. The debt is typically expressed as a percentage of GDP, allowing comparison across countries and over time.",
    detailed: "The national debt grows when annual borrowing exceeds repayments and shrinks in real terms when GDP growth or inflation outpaces new borrowing. Servicing the debt requires interest payments, which become a significant government expenditure when debt levels are high. Whether national debt is problematic depends on what financed it: debt incurred for productive investment may pay for itself through higher future growth, while debt funding current consumption simply shifts the burden to future taxpayers. The UK's national debt rose sharply after the 2008 financial crisis and again during COVID-19, exceeding 100% of GDP. Common mistake: Students confuse the national debt (the stock of accumulated borrowing) with the budget deficit (the annual flow of new borrowing).",
    seeAlso: ["budget-deficit", "fiscal-policy", "government-bonds", "debt-to-gdp-ratio", "crowding-out"],
