    term: "National income",
    brief: "The total value of all goods and services produced by a country's residents, plus net income from abroad, over a given period.",
    more: "National income can be measured three ways: the output method (summing value added), the income method (summing wages, profits, and rents), and the expenditure method (summing consumption, investment, government spending, and net exports). All three should produce the same figure in principle.",
    detailed: "National income includes income earned by UK residents from assets abroad, minus income paid to foreign residents from UK assets; this distinguishes it from GDP, which measures output within borders regardless of ownership. Gross national income (GNI) is the standard measure. National income figures are used to track economic growth, compare living standards, and assess the tax base available to governments. Seasonal adjustment and revisions mean initial estimates are often revised significantly. Common mistake: Students treat GDP and national income as identical. GDP measures domestic output; national income adjusts for cross-border income flows.",
