    detailed: "Nominal GDP is useful for assessing the current money value of an economy: for example, when comparing government debt to GDP or setting tax revenue expectations. However, it is misleading for tracking growth over time or comparing countries with different inflation rates. To convert nominal to real GDP, economists divide by a price index such as the GDP deflator. A country experiencing high inflation may report impressive nominal GDP growth while real living standards stagnate. Common mistake: Students cite nominal GDP growth as evidence of economic success without checking whether inflation accounts for most of the increase.",
