    brief: "The amount by which actual GDP exceeds the economy's productive potential, indicating overheating and inflationary pressure.",
    more: "A positive output gap emerges when aggregate demand grows faster than supply capacity, pushing unemployment below its natural rate and creating labour shortages. Firms face rising wage demands and pass costs on through higher prices.",
    detailed: "Signs of a positive output gap include falling unemployment, rising inflation, capacity constraints, and labour market tightness. It typically occurs near the peak of the economic cycle when confidence is high and spending strong. Central banks respond by raising interest rates to cool demand; governments may tighten fiscal policy. A sustained positive output gap is unsustainable because inflation accelerates, eventually requiring a painful correction. The output gap is difficult to measure precisely because potential output is estimated, not observed. Common mistake: Students sometimes assume a positive output gap is desirable because GDP is high, but it signals unsustainable growth that will reverse.",
    seeAlso: ["negative-output-gap", "economic-cycle", "demand-pull-inflation", "long-run-aggregate-supply", "natural-rate-of-unemployment"],
