    group: "Fiscal Policy",
    term: "Progressive tax",
    brief: "A tax where the proportion of income paid rises as income increases.",
    more: "Higher earners face higher marginal tax rates, so they pay a larger share of their income in tax. This redistributes income from rich to poor and reduces inequality in disposable incomes.",
    detailed: "The UK income tax is progressive: the personal allowance means low earners pay no tax, while additional-rate taxpayers pay 45% on income above £125,140. Progressivity is measured by comparing average tax rates across the income distribution, not just marginal rates. Progressive taxes are justified on ability-to-pay grounds and diminishing marginal utility; a pound means less to a millionaire than to someone on minimum wage. Critics argue steep progressivity discourages effort and encourages tax avoidance. Common mistake: Students confuse marginal and average rates. A higher marginal rate does not mean all income is taxed at that rate, only income in that band.",
