    group: "Fiscal Policy",
    term: "Public expenditure",
    brief: "Total spending by the government on goods, services, transfers, and debt interest.",
    more: "It includes current spending on day-to-day services like healthcare and education, capital spending on infrastructure, transfer payments such as pensions and benefits, and interest on the national debt. Public expenditure is a major component of aggregate demand.",
    detailed: "Public expenditure is classified as either capital or current. Capital expenditure creates assets with lasting value: roads, hospitals, schools; current expenditure covers ongoing costs like wages and consumables. Transfer payments redistribute income but do not directly purchase goods or services, so they affect aggregate demand only when recipients spend them. In the UK, public spending accounts for roughly 40 to 45% of GDP in normal times, rising during crises. Fiscal rules often distinguish between borrowing for investment and borrowing for current spending. Common mistake: Students sometimes include transfer payments when calculating the government's direct contribution to GDP; only government consumption and investment count toward GDP, and transfers are excluded until spent by recipients.",
