    term: "Purchasing power parity (PPP)",
    brief: "An exchange rate adjustment that equalises the purchasing power of different currencies by accounting for price level differences between countries.",
    more: "Market exchange rates often diverge from PPP because they reflect capital flows and speculation, not just goods prices. PPP-adjusted figures give a more accurate comparison of real living standards across countries.",
    detailed: "PPP is calculated by comparing the cost of a standardised basket of goods across countries, then deriving the exchange rate that would make those baskets cost the same. The World Bank and IMF use PPP to compare GDP across countries, since market exchange rates can dramatically under- or overstate poorer countries' output. India's GDP, for example, rises significantly when measured at PPP rather than market rates, because domestic prices are lower. PPP works best for internationally traded goods; local services often diverge due to differing labour costs. Common mistake: Students confuse PPP with market exchange rates. PPP is a theoretical rate based on price equivalence, not the rate at which currencies actually trade.",
