    curricula: ['aqa-alevel', 'ap-economics'],
    group: "Money & Monetary Policy",
    term: "Quantitative tightening",
    brief: "The process by which a central bank reduces its balance sheet by selling bonds or allowing them to mature without reinvestment, withdrawing money from the economy.",
    more: "Quantitative tightening reverses the expansion of the money supply created by quantitative easing. As bonds are sold or redeemed, bank reserves fall, putting upward pressure on long-term interest rates and tightening financial conditions.",
    detailed: "The Bank of England began quantitative tightening in 2022 after years of asset purchases had expanded its balance sheet dramatically. The process must be managed carefully: selling bonds too quickly could destabilise financial markets by flooding them with supply and pushing yields up sharply. QT works alongside Bank Rate rises to tighten monetary policy, but its effects are less predictable and harder to calibrate. Central banks typically prefer passive QT, letting bonds mature, over active sales to minimise market disruption. Common mistake: Students sometimes treat QT as simply the opposite of QE with symmetric effects; in practice, markets may react more sharply to tightening than easing because rising yields impose immediate losses on bondholders.",
