    group: "National Income & Growth",
    term: "Real GDP",
    brief: "GDP adjusted for inflation, measuring the volume of output at constant prices.",
    more: "By removing the effect of price changes, real GDP allows meaningful comparison of output over time. An economy with rising nominal GDP but higher inflation may have stagnant or falling real GDP.",
    detailed: "Real GDP is calculated by valuing current output at the prices of a base year, stripping out inflation to reveal changes in actual production. It is the measure used for growth rates and international comparisons of productive capacity. Chain-linking updates the base year continuously to reflect changing spending patterns, improving accuracy. Real GDP growth is a key indicator of economic performance, though it ignores quality improvements and new products not in the base-year basket. Common mistake: Students sometimes calculate real GDP by simply subtracting the inflation rate from nominal GDP; the correct method uses a price index to deflate nominal figures.",
    seeAlso: ["nominal-gdp", "economic-growth", "consumer-prices-index-cpi", "gdp-deflator", "base-year"],
