    group: "National Income & Growth",
    term: "Real GDP per capita",
    brief: "Real GDP divided by the population, measuring average output per person at constant prices.",
    more: "This adjusts for both inflation and population size, providing a better indicator of typical living standards than total GDP. A country with high GDP but a large population may have low GDP per capita.",
    detailed: "Real GDP per capita is widely used to compare living standards across countries and over time. However, it is an average that conceals inequality: a country with high GDP per capita may still have widespread poverty if income is concentrated. It also inherits GDP's limitations, excluding non-market activity, leisure, and environmental costs. For international comparisons, purchasing power parity adjustments improve accuracy by accounting for price differences between countries. Common mistake: Students treat real GDP per capita as a direct measure of wellbeing; it captures average output, not how that output is distributed or whether it translates into quality of life.",
