    brief: "A tax where the proportion of income paid falls as income increases.",
    more: "Even if the tax rate is flat, regressive taxes take a larger share of income from the poor than from the rich. Most indirect taxes are regressive because lower-income households spend a higher proportion of their income on taxed goods.",
    detailed: "VAT at 20% is regressive: a household spending all its income on VAT-able goods pays 20% of income in VAT, while a wealthy household saving half its income pays only 10%. Excise duties on essentials like fuel are particularly regressive. Governments sometimes mitigate this by zero-rating necessities; food and children's clothing are VAT-exempt in the UK. Poll taxes, which charge a flat amount per person regardless of income, are the most regressive form. Common mistake: Students sometimes label VAT 'proportional' because the rate is flat, but regressivity refers to the share of income paid, not the rate on spending.",
