    group: "Unemployment & Labour",
    term: "Seasonal unemployment",
    brief: "Unemployment caused by predictable, recurring fluctuations in labour demand linked to seasons or holidays.",
    more: "Industries such as agriculture, tourism, and retail experience regular peaks and troughs in demand, creating temporary joblessness at certain times of year. Because these patterns are predictable, official statistics are often seasonally adjusted to reveal underlying trends.",
    detailed: "Seasonal unemployment differs from cyclical unemployment in being regular and foreseeable rather than driven by macroeconomic shocks. Workers in affected industries may anticipate spells of unemployment and adjust their savings or seek temporary contracts elsewhere. Policies to address it include retraining workers for year-round employment or promoting counter-seasonal industries in affected regions. Seasonal adjustment removes these predictable swings from data, allowing analysts to identify genuine changes in labour market conditions. Common mistake: Students sometimes treat seasonal unemployment as a minor issue; in regions heavily reliant on tourism or agriculture, it can cause significant hardship and income volatility.",
    seeAlso: ["cyclical-unemployment", "structural-unemployment", "frictional-unemployment", "unemployment-rate"],
