    curricula: ['aqa-alevel', 'ap-economics'],
    group: "Unemployment & Labour",
    term: "Short-run Phillips curve",
    brief: "A curve showing an inverse relationship between unemployment and inflation at a given level of inflation expectations.",
    more: "The short-run Phillips curve suggests policymakers face a trade-off: reducing unemployment requires accepting higher inflation, and vice versa. The curve shifts when inflation expectations change; if workers expect higher inflation, they demand higher wages, pushing the curve upward.",
    detailed: "The short-run Phillips curve reflects the observation that when unemployment falls below its natural rate, labour markets tighten, wages rise, and firms pass on higher costs as inflation. Expansionary policy can temporarily reduce unemployment by moving along the curve, but only while expectations remain anchored. Once workers and firms adjust their expectations to the higher inflation, the curve shifts upward, returning unemployment to its natural rate at a higher inflation level. This expectation-augmented view, developed by Friedman and Phelps, challenged the idea of a permanent trade-off. Common mistake: Students assume the trade-off is permanent. In the short run, inflation expectations are sticky, but once they adjust, the economy moves to a new short-run curve at the natural rate of unemployment.",
    seeAlso: ["long-run-phillips-curve", "natural-rate-of-unemployment", "inflation-expectations", "demand-pull-inflation", "nairu"],
