    group: "National Income & Growth",
    term: "Standard of living",
    brief: "The level of material welfare available to an individual or population, typically measured by real income per capita and access to goods and services.",
    more: "Higher real GDP per capita generally indicates a higher standard of living, but the measure ignores distribution, working hours, and non-material factors such as health and leisure. Broader measures like the Human Development Index attempt to capture these dimensions.",
    detailed: "Economists distinguish material living standards, covering purchasing power, housing quality, and access to consumer goods, from broader wellbeing, which includes life expectancy, education, environmental quality, and personal freedom. A country may have high GDP per capita yet poor healthcare or extreme inequality, limiting how far average income translates into actual welfare. International comparisons require purchasing power parity adjustments, since a given income buys more in low-price countries. Rising living standards over time reflect economic growth, but sustainability and environmental costs are increasingly factored into assessments. Common mistake: Students equate GDP per capita with standard of living directly; GDP per capita is an input to living standards, not a comprehensive measure of them.",
