    group: "Fiscal Policy",
    term: "Structural budget balance",
    brief: "The budget balance that would exist if the economy were operating at its full potential output, removing the effects of the economic cycle.",
    more: "During recessions, tax revenues fall and welfare spending rises automatically, worsening the deficit without any policy change. The structural balance strips out these cyclical effects to reveal the underlying fiscal position.",
    detailed: "A structural deficit indicates the government would still be borrowing even at full employment, suggesting spending commitments exceed revenues on a permanent basis. This requires policy action to correct, unlike a cyclical deficit which closes automatically as the economy recovers. Calculating the structural balance requires estimating potential output, which is inherently uncertain and subject to revision. Fiscal rules often target the structural balance rather than the headline balance to allow automatic stabilisers to operate during downturns. Common mistake: Students assume any deficit during a recession is purely cyclical; in practice, most economies carry a structural deficit alongside the cyclical component.",
