    group: "Money & Monetary Policy",
    term: "Systemic risk",
    brief: "The risk that the failure of one financial institution triggers a cascade of failures across the entire financial system.",
    more: "Systemic risk arises from interconnections between banks through lending, derivatives, and payment systems, meaning one institution's collapse can impose losses on others. The 2008 collapse of Lehman Brothers demonstrated how a single failure could freeze global credit markets.",
    detailed: "Financial institutions are systemically important if their failure would cause widespread disruption; these are designated 'too big to fail' or, more precisely, 'systemically important financial institutions' (SIFIs). Systemic risk justifies macroprudential regulation: policies aimed at the stability of the financial system as a whole, not just individual firms. Tools include higher capital buffers for large banks, stress testing, and limits on interconnected exposures. Central banks act as lenders of last resort to prevent liquidity crises becoming systemic, though this creates moral hazard. Common mistake: Students often treat systemic risk as simply meaning 'big risk'; the defining feature is contagion, where problems spread through the system regardless of whether other institutions are fundamentally sound.",
    seeAlso: ["moral-hazard", "financial-stability", "macroprudential-policy", "lender-of-last-resort", "bank-run"],
