    more: "Tariffs protect domestic producers by making imports less competitive, generate government revenue, and may be used to retaliate against trading partners. They reduce consumer surplus by raising prices and create deadweight welfare loss.",
    detailed: "A tariff shifts the supply curve of imports upward by the tariff amount, raising the domestic price and reducing the quantity imported. Domestic producers gain from higher prices and increased market share; the government gains tariff revenue on remaining imports; but consumers lose more than these gains combined, creating net welfare loss. The incidence of a tariff depends on demand and supply elasticities: where import supply is highly elastic, consumers bear most of the burden. Tariffs are more transparent than quotas and generate revenue, making them the least distortionary form of protection. Common mistake: Students often calculate tariff revenue incorrectly. It equals the tariff rate multiplied by the quantity of imports after the tariff is imposed, not before.",
