    brief: "Compulsory payments levied by the government on income, spending, or wealth to finance public expenditure and influence economic behaviour.",
    more: "Direct taxes fall on income and wealth, such as income tax and inheritance tax; indirect taxes fall on spending, such as VAT and excise duties. Beyond raising revenue, taxation is used to correct market failures, redistribute income, and manage aggregate demand.",
    detailed: "Progressive taxes take a larger proportion of income from higher earners, reducing inequality; regressive taxes take a larger proportion from lower earners, as with VAT on essentials. Taxation affects incentives: high marginal income tax rates may discourage work effort, while taxes on negative externalities like carbon emissions can improve resource allocation. The tax base and tax rates together determine revenue; the Laffer curve suggests that beyond a certain rate, higher taxes reduce revenue by shrinking the tax base. Fiscal drag occurs when inflation pushes earners into higher tax bands without any real income gain. Common mistake: Students often assume all taxes reduce economic efficiency, but corrective taxes on externalities can actually improve efficiency by aligning private and social costs.",
    seeAlso: ["direct-tax", "indirect-tax", "progressive-tax", "regressive-tax", "fiscal-policy", "hypothecated-tax", "laffer-curve"],
