    term: "Terms of trade",
    brief: "The ratio of a country's export prices to its import prices, expressed as an index.",
    more: "Calculated as (index of export prices / index of import prices) × 100. An improvement in the terms of trade means export prices rise relative to import prices, so fewer exports are needed to buy a given quantity of imports.",
    detailed: "Rising terms of trade increase a country's purchasing power over foreign goods, as each unit of exports buys more imports. However, the effect on the current account is ambiguous: higher export prices may reduce export volumes if demand is elastic. Developing countries dependent on primary commodity exports often face volatile terms of trade as global commodity prices fluctuate. A deterioration in the terms of trade, where export prices fall relative to import prices, can cause a transfer of real income abroad. Common mistake: Students often assume improving terms of trade always benefit the economy; if the improvement reflects falling competitiveness rather than rising demand, export volumes may collapse.",
