    term: "Unemployment",
    brief: "The number of people without work who are actively seeking employment and available to start.",
    more: "The ILO definition, used in the Labour Force Survey, counts someone as unemployed if they have looked for work in the past four weeks and could start within two weeks. The unemployment rate expresses this as a percentage of the labour force.",
    detailed: "Unemployment imposes costs on individuals through lost income and skills, on the government through benefit payments and forgone tax revenue, and on the economy through lost output. It has several causes: cyclical unemployment from weak demand, structural unemployment from skills mismatches, and frictional unemployment from job search between positions. The natural rate of unemployment is the level consistent with stable inflation, reflecting structural and frictional factors only. Full employment does not mean zero unemployment; some transitional joblessness is inevitable in a dynamic economy. Common mistake: Students often confuse the claimant count (benefit recipients) with ILO unemployment. The two measures differ because not all unemployed people claim benefits and not all claimants are ILO-unemployed.",
