    brief: "Unemployment where individuals choose not to accept available jobs at the prevailing wage rate.",
    more: "This may occur because workers are searching for better-paid roles, the replacement ratio makes benefits attractive relative to work, or non-wage factors such as location or conditions make available jobs unacceptable. Classical economists emphasise voluntary unemployment as the dominant form when labour markets clear.",
    detailed: "Voluntary unemployment is central to the classical view that unemployment results from workers' choices rather than deficient demand. If wages were fully flexible, the labour market would clear at full employment, leaving only those who voluntarily reject work at the market wage. Policies to reduce voluntary unemployment focus on supply-side measures: lowering benefits, improving job information, or increasing work incentives through the tax system. Keynesian economists counter that much observed unemployment is involuntary, resulting from insufficient aggregate demand. Common mistake: Students sometimes assume voluntary unemployment is not a genuine problem, but high replacement ratios or poor incentives can trap people out of work even when jobs exist.",
