    term: "Basket of goods",
    brief: "The representative collection of goods and services used to measure changes in the price level over time.",
    more: "The basket reflects the spending patterns of a typical household. Its composition is updated periodically to account for changing consumption habits, such as the addition of streaming services and removal of obsolete products.",
    detailed: "In the UK, the Office for National Statistics constructs the CPI basket by surveying actual household spending. Each item is weighted according to its share of total spending, so a rise in food prices has a larger impact on measured inflation than a rise in the price of postage stamps. The basket contains around 700 items across categories including food, clothing, housing, transport, and recreation. Because the basket is fixed between updates, it can overstate inflation if consumers switch to cheaper substitutes, or understate it if new goods are not captured quickly enough. Common mistake: Students describe the basket as fixed permanently. It is updated each year, though not in response to short-term price changes.",
