    detailed: "The concept looks clean in theory but is notoriously hard to measure in practice: estimates of the output gap, which proxies spare capacity, are routinely revised after the fact, meaning policymakers are often acting on figures that turn out to be wrong. This matters because if the Bank of England underestimates remaining spare capacity, it may tighten policy too early and choke off a recovery that still had room to run without inflation. There is also a genuine debate about whether spare capacity created during a deep recession can ever be fully reclaimed, since prolonged disuse causes capital to depreciate and workers to lose skills, permanently shrinking potential output rather than leaving it intact and waiting. Common mistake: Students treat spare capacity as a simple green light for stimulus, ignoring that the size, location, and quality of idle resources determine whether extra demand produces output gains or just drives up costs in bottlenecked sectors.",
